30-40% of the patients of a general practitioner (GP) suffer from a psychogenic disorder. Only 50% of these patients are sufficiently diagnosed by their GPs. The quality of the doctor-patient interaction is of outstanding importance for the diagnostic process. The quality of the physician's conversation with the patient is the result of a reciprocal attunement between physician and patient. Training programmes aiming at improving the basic psychosomatic competence did not show the expected effect possibly due to their failure to take into account the importance of improving the interactional competence. Improving the interactional competence is a central issue in the Düsseldorf training program for psychosomatic basic care. This program will be explained amd discussed.  
